Dear Hiring Team,

It is with great pleasure that I submit my candidacy for the *Junior Engineer* role with *Canonical*. I bring over three years of professional experience building production-grade backend systems and automation tooling, along with a strong academic foundation as a Master of Science in Computer Science graduate from Pace University, NY.

Through my experience across two engineering roles, I have built and delivered systems that directly reflect the technical depth this position demands — designing, debugging, and shipping *robust*, *resilient* software with a focus on *quality* and *performance*. As a Software Engineer at Sperse, I engineered an *open source*-style *automation* layer in *Python* that translates natural-language intents into safe, validated tool calls across 1,000+ platform endpoints, backed by a *CI/CD*-integrated *testing* and *observability* pipeline using LangSmith and Langfuse for tracing, structured logs, and evaluation hooks. I also architected a *concurrent multi-agent* orchestration system using LangChain and LangGraph, coordinating *distributed* tool execution with *resilient* state management — reducing end-to-end latency by 60% and LLM API costs by 50% through targeted *performance* profiling. Prior to Sperse, at Qualitest, I designed and shipped a cloud-agnostic Storage Service in *Python* with PostgreSQL and Redis across Google Cloud Storage, S3, and MinIO, and built backend *automation* workflows using AWS Step Functions and Lambda — applying systematic *debugging* and retry logic to ensure *reliable* execution of long-running jobs. Together, these roles have prepared me to contribute meaningfully to Ubuntu Engineering's core responsibilities: designing, building, and shipping foundational software with the rigor and operational discipline Canonical's globally distributed teams demand.

My academic and personal project work has given me direct experience with the systems-level engineering and *open source* community collaboration central to this role. As an AI Researcher at the Pace Artificial Intelligence Lab, I managed the full model lifecycle on a *Linux* HPC cluster — from training and fine-tuning to *shipping* inference — and authored *technical documentation* while delivering workshops for 50+ students, collaborating asynchronously as part of a *globally distributed* research team. Outside of work, I built *Dark Factory* in *Rust* as a *foundational systems software* tool that owns CLI I/O via PTY on *Linux*, intercepting and logging every shell command before execution, and implements *distributed* session coordination via Y-crdt CRDTs for *resilient* multi-node orchestration — a project that reflects my passion for systems software, *open source* tooling, and engineering with precision.

I have always been passionate about *bringing free software to the widest audience* and *enabling anyone, anywhere, to pursue their ambitions regardless of their resources* — the twin pillars of Canonical's mission. The idea that a researcher in the furthest corner of the world can use Ubuntu on exactly the same terms as a startup in San Francisco is not just an inspiring goal; it is the kind of mission I want to build toward every day. I would love to discuss my interest in this position with your team and can be reached at #ph or #eml. Thank you for your time and consideration, I look forward to connecting!

